contents.name: Owner
contents.description:
The owner of equity claims under IFRS refers to parties who hold equity instruments (such as shares or similar ownership interests) and have a residual interest in the entity’s net assets after deducting all liabilities. 
These owners are entitled to the entity’s profits, dividends, and remaining assets upon liquidation, while also bearing the residual risks of ownership.

contents.name: Asset
contents.description:
A present economic resource controlled by the entity as a result of past events. 


An entity controls an economic resource if it has the present ability to direct the use of the economic resource and obtain the economic benefits that may flow from it,  
either directly or through an agent acting on behalf of the controlling entity.   
Control includes the present ability to prevent other parties from directing the use of the economic resource and from obtaining the economic benefits that may flow from it.   
An agent may facilitate the obtaining of economic benefits or the prevention of others from obtaining such benefits, but the principal retains ultimate control.   
It follows that, if one party controls an economic resource, no other party controls that resource.

contents.name: Property
contents.description:
Property refers to any physical object, intangible resource, financial right, or contractual entitlement controlled by an entity, 
which is capable of generating measurable economic benefits through ownership, use, transfer, exchange, or other forms of exploitation. 
This includes the right to receive services or other economic benefits under enforceable agreements.

contents.name: Economic Resource
contents.description:
An Economic Resource is a right, 
enabling the overarching commitment of an enterprise to exchange economic resources, 
which has the potential to produce entitlement rights to economic benefits. 
An economic resource, such as homeownership, is a social relator mediating an enterprise with the market society or participants. 
It includes a mode of commitment to exchange—the Enabling Right (e.g., the right to sell a house)—
paired with a reciprocal Benefit Potential mode (e.g., receiving a payment or a receivable). 
Enabling rights may emerge from owning a property (e.g., a house), or the right to transfer a claim (e.g., a mortgage).

An obligation to exchange refers to a present commitment by an entity to transfer economic resources (e.g., cash, goods, or services) to another party as a result of a binding agreement or past event.
This concept typically aligns with the definition of a liability under IFRS.
Conditional to Right, Obligation to Resource Transfer

contents.name: Other-Party
contents.description:
An Enterprise is an organization and a market participant.
Enterprises claim economic resources (assets) against other parties and face claims from other parties (liabilities and equity claims).
They also exhibit a commitment toward owners and are enabled to use resources and claims in economic exchanges and other activities designed to realize economic resources to gain economic benefits.

properties.name: Role Type
properties.description: The term "going concern" refers to the assumption that a business will continue its operations into the foreseeable future and has neither the intention nor the need to liquidate or significantly reduce its activities. This concept is fundamental in accounting and financial reporting, as it influences how assets and liabilities are valued and how financial statements are prepared.

contents.name: Exchange Type
contents.description:
An Economic Exchange is a reciprocal transaction between market participants that entails the transfer of economic resources.
In return, each participant becomes entitled to commensurate economic benefits, with the entire exchange conducted under the going concern objective.

contents.name: Receipt Recognition
contents.description:
Outflow/Transfer events occur either due to unexpected outflow events arising from environmental or market conditions or 
when an Obligation to Exchange triggers Obligation Fulfillment event. 
Transfer may involve Provision of Services or Assumption of Claims (Transfer of Rights enabling Other Party to Transfer Claims). 
Outflows/Transfers ontologically always result in Decreases in Equity (Expenses) typically accompanied by Decreases in Assets or Increases in Liabilities.

contents.name: Realization Completion
contents.description:
Obligation Fulfillment also includes Right Accrual event that brings about the Exchange Contract into the Claim of Entity phase and leads to Increase in Equity. 
Ultimately, extinguishing the obligations and rights leads the exchange contract into its Extinguished Contract phase.

contents.name: Exchange Right
contents.description:
A right to exchange refers to a legal or constructive entitlement held by an entity to receive economic resources (e.g., cash, goods, or services) from another party under a binding agreement or arrangement. 
This concept aligns with the definition of an asset under IFRS. 
Conditional to Obligation, Right to Benefit Receipt

contents.name: Exchange Contract
contents.description:
A combined right and obligation to exchange economic resources. 
The right and obligation are interdependent and cannot be separated. Hence, the combined right and obligation constitute a single asset or liability.
